555  // Phantom persistents work like weak persistents, except that the pointer to
556  // the object being collected is not available in the finalization callback.
557  // This enables the garbage collector to collect the object and any objects
558  // it references transitively in one GC cycle. At the moment you can either
559  // specify a parameter for the callback or the location of two internal
560  // fields in the dying object.

1095  length(0),
1096  rejected(false),
1097  buffer_policy(BufferNotOwned) {}
1098 
1099  // If buffer_policy is BufferNotOwned, the caller keeps the ownership of
1100  // data and guarantees that it stays alive until the CachedData object is
1101  // destroyed. If the policy is BufferOwned, the given data will be deleted
1102  // (with delete[]) when the CachedData object is destroyed.
1103  CachedData(const uint8_t* data, int length,
1104  BufferPolicy buffer_policy = BufferNotOwned);
1105  ~CachedData();

1107  // which will be called when V8 no longer needs the data.
1108  const uint8_t* data;
1109  int length;
1110  bool rejected;
1111  BufferPolicy buffer_policy;
1112 
1113  private:
1114  // Prevent copying. Not implemented.
1115  CachedData(const CachedData&);
1116  CachedData& operator=(const CachedData&);
1117  };

4535 struct JitCodeEvent {
4536  enum EventType {
4537  CODE_ADDED,
4538  CODE_MOVED,
4539  CODE_REMOVED,
4540  CODE_ADD_LINE_POS_INFO,
4541  CODE_START_LINE_INFO_RECORDING,
4542  CODE_END_LINE_INFO_RECORDING
4543  };
4544  // Definition of the code position type. The "POSITION" type means the place
4545  // in the source code which are of interest when making stack traces to
4546  // pin-point the source location of a stack frame as close as possible.
4547  // The "STATEMENT_POSITION" means the place at the beginning of each
4548  // statement, and is used to indicate possible break locations.
4549  enum PositionType { POSITION, STATEMENT_POSITION };
4550 
4551  // Type of event.
4552  EventType type;
4553  // Start of the instructions.
4554  void* code_start;
4555  // Size of the instructions.
4556  size_t code_len;
4557  // Script info for CODE_ADDED event.
4558  Handle<UnboundScript> script;
4559  // User-defined data for *_LINE_INFO_* event. It's used to hold the source
4560  // code line information which is returned from the
4561  // CODE_START_LINE_INFO_RECORDING event. And it's passed to subsequent
4562  // CODE_ADD_LINE_POS_INFO and CODE_END_LINE_INFO_RECORDING events.
4563  void* user_data;

6143 const int kApiPointerSize = sizeof(void*); // NOLINT
6144 const int kApiIntSize = sizeof(int); // NOLINT
6145 const int kApiInt64Size = sizeof(int64_t); // NOLINT
6146 
6147 // Tag information for HeapObject.
6148 const int kHeapObjectTag = 1;
6149 const int kHeapObjectTagSize = 2;
6150 const intptr_t kHeapObjectTagMask = (1 << kHeapObjectTagSize) - 1;
6151 
6152 // Tag information for Smi.
6153 const int kSmiTag = 0;
6154 const int kSmiTagSize = 1;
6155 const intptr_t kSmiTagMask = (1 << kSmiTagSize) - 1;
6156 
6157 template <size_t ptr_size> struct SmiTagging;
6158 
6159 template<int kSmiShiftSize>
6160 V8_INLINE internal::Object* IntToSmi(int value) {
6161  int smi_shift_bits = kSmiTagSize + kSmiShiftSize;
6162  uintptr_t tagged_value =
6163  (static_cast<uintptr_t>(value) << smi_shift_bits) | kSmiTag;
6164  return reinterpret_cast<internal::Object*>(tagged_value);
6165 }
6166 
6167 // Smi constants for 32-bit systems.
6168 template <> struct SmiTagging<4> {
6169  enum { kSmiShiftSize = 0, kSmiValueSize = 31 };
6170  static int SmiShiftSize() { return kSmiShiftSize; }
6171  static int SmiValueSize() { return kSmiValueSize; }
6172  V8_INLINE static int SmiToInt(const internal::Object* value) {
6173  int shift_bits = kSmiTagSize + kSmiShiftSize;
6174  // Throw away top 32 bits and shift down (requires >> to be sign extending).
6175  return static_cast<int>(reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(value)) >> shift_bits;
6176  }
6177  V8_INLINE static internal::Object* IntToSmi(int value) {
6178  return internal::IntToSmi<kSmiShiftSize>(value);
6179  }
6180  V8_INLINE static bool IsValidSmi(intptr_t value) {
6181  // To be representable as an tagged small integer, the two
6182  // most-significant bits of 'value' must be either 00 or 11 due to
6183  // sign-extension. To check this we add 01 to the two
6184  // most-significant bits, and check if the most-significant bit is 0
6185  //
6186  // CAUTION: The original code below:
6187  // bool result = ((value + 0x40000000) & 0x80000000) == 0;
6188  // may lead to incorrect results according to the C language spec, and
6189  // in fact doesn't work correctly with gcc4.1.1 in some cases: The
6190  // compiler may produce undefined results in case of signed integer
6191  // overflow. The computation must be done w/ unsigned ints.
6192  return static_cast<uintptr_t>(value + 0x40000000U) < 0x80000000U;
6193  }
6194 };
6195 
6196 // Smi constants for 64-bit systems.
6197 template <> struct SmiTagging<8> {
6198  enum { kSmiShiftSize = 31, kSmiValueSize = 32 };
6199  static int SmiShiftSize() { return kSmiShiftSize; }
6200  static int SmiValueSize() { return kSmiValueSize; }
6201  V8_INLINE static int SmiToInt(const internal::Object* value) {
6202  int shift_bits = kSmiTagSize + kSmiShiftSize;
6203  // Shift down and throw away top 32 bits.
6204  return static_cast<int>(reinterpret_cast<intptr_t>(value) >> shift_bits);
6205  }
6206  V8_INLINE static internal::Object* IntToSmi(int value) {
6207  return internal::IntToSmi<kSmiShiftSize>(value);
6208  }
6209  V8_INLINE static bool IsValidSmi(intptr_t value) {
6210  // To be representable as a long smi, the value must be a 32-bit integer.
6211  return (value == static_cast<int32_t>(value));
6212  }
6213 };
6214

6216 const int kSmiShiftSize = PlatformSmiTagging::kSmiShiftSize;
6217 const int kSmiValueSize = PlatformSmiTagging::kSmiValueSize;
6218 V8_INLINE static bool SmiValuesAre31Bits() { return kSmiValueSize == 31; }
6219 V8_INLINE static bool SmiValuesAre32Bits() { return kSmiValueSize == 32; }

6845 Local<Value> Object::GetInternalField(int index) {
6846 #ifndef V8_ENABLE_CHECKS
6847  typedef internal::Object O;
6848  typedef internal::HeapObject HO;
6849  typedef internal::Internals I;
6850  O* obj = *reinterpret_cast<O**>(this);
6851  // Fast path: If the object is a plain JSObject, which is the common case, we
6852  // know where to find the internal fields and can return the value directly.
6853  if (I::GetInstanceType(obj) == I::kJSObjectType) {
6854  int offset = I::kJSObjectHeaderSize + (internal::kApiPointerSize * index);
6855  O* value = I::ReadField<O*>(obj, offset);
6856  O** result = HandleScope::CreateHandle(reinterpret_cast<HO*>(obj), value);
6857  return Local<Value>(reinterpret_cast<Value*>(result));
6858  }
6859 #endif
6860  return SlowGetInternalField(index);
6861 }

6864 void* Object::GetAlignedPointerFromInternalField(int index) {
6865 #ifndef V8_ENABLE_CHECKS
6866  typedef internal::Object O;
6867  typedef internal::Internals I;
6868  O* obj = *reinterpret_cast<O**>(this);
6869  // Fast path: If the object is a plain JSObject, which is the common case, we
6870  // know where to find the internal fields and can return the value directly.
6871  if (V8_LIKELY(I::GetInstanceType(obj) == I::kJSObjectType)) {
6872  int offset = I::kJSObjectHeaderSize + (internal::kApiPointerSize * index);
6873  return I::ReadField<void*>(obj, offset);

6875 #endif

7347 int64_t Isolate::AdjustAmountOfExternalAllocatedMemory(
7348  int64_t change_in_bytes) {
7349  typedef internal::Internals I;
7350  int64_t* amount_of_external_allocated_memory =
7351  reinterpret_cast<int64_t*>(reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(this) +
7352  I::kAmountOfExternalAllocatedMemoryOffset);
7353  int64_t* amount_of_external_allocated_memory_at_last_global_gc =
7354  reinterpret_cast<int64_t*>(
7355  reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(this) +
7356  I::kAmountOfExternalAllocatedMemoryAtLastGlobalGCOffset);
7357  int64_t amount = *amount_of_external_allocated_memory + change_in_bytes;
7358  if (change_in_bytes > 0 &&
7359  amount - *amount_of_external_allocated_memory_at_last_global_gc >
7360  I::kExternalAllocationLimit) {
7361  CollectAllGarbage("external memory allocation limit reached.");
7362  }
7363  *amount_of_external_allocated_memory = amount;
7364  return *amount_of_external_allocated_memory;
7365 }
